{
  "answer": "Chapters 6 and 9 of Charles Comte's Traité de Législation Vol I (slug: charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2) form a paired critique-and-alternative argument about the proper relationship between civil law and morality.\n\nChapter 6 is a sustained demolition of Rousseau's Social Contract as a foundation for civil law. Its central relevance to the morality/law question is this: Rousseau fused civil law and morality by making them both spring simultaneously from the social pact — before the pact, 'actions have no morality'; after it, 'justice is substituted for instinct, actions take on a morality they did not have.' Civil law, on this view, is the source of morality. Comte rejects this fusion as both historically fictitious and logically self-defeating: Rousseau himself invokes pre-conventional natural rights (e.g., against slavery) that would have to be morally binding before any pact — which contradicts his own premise that the pact creates morality. Comte's conclusion is that morality cannot be derived from or created by civil law. Societies, laws, and property 'sustain themselves by the force inherent in their nature,' not by convention.\n\nChapter 9 then examines the utilitarian alternative (Bentham): founding both morality AND legislation on the principle of utility. Comte accepts the principle as correct but criticises Bentham's method: he makes utility a prescriptive duty ('public happiness ought to be the object of the legislator') rather than a factual observation. This is Comte's central methodological distinction — science expounds facts about what produces good or evil for the whole human race; governments (civil law) then act on those facts. 'By applying these ideas to morality and legislation, one arrives at the idea that, to judge actions or laws, one must judge the effects they produce… relative to the entire human race.'\n\nWhere Comte folds morality into civil law: Both share the same empirical ground — the observable consequences of actions and laws for human welfare. Moral rules and legal rules alike emerge from the factual study of utility. In this sense, moral science and the science of legislation are continuous: 'rules, duties can emerge from the exposition of facts; they can be consequences of it.' Civil law that is properly grounded will reflect the same utilitarian facts that ground moral judgment.\n\nWhere Comte keeps them apart: (1) Morality (as the empirical science of utility) is logically prior to and independent of civil law — the legislator does not create moral reality, he acts on it. Chapter 6's critique of Rousseau establishes this firmly: civil law cannot be the source of morality. (2) There is a structural distinction between the scholar (who observes and expounds facts) and the government (which forbids, commands, and enforces). The scientist of legislation spreads light; governments put rules into practice. Thus the moral-scientific layer and the legal-prescriptive layer remain methodologically distinct even as they share the same utilitarian content.\n\nIn short: Chapter 6 destroys the Rousseauan view that civil law creates morality by fiat. Chapter 9 replaces it with the view that both morality and civil law must be grounded in the same empirical utility facts — but the science of observing those facts (morality) remains prior to and independent of the practical art of law-giving (civil law). Morality grounds law; law does not ground morality.",
